---
/**
 * Tutorial 01 -- Your First Boundary
 *
 * A "boundary" is the core primitive of czap. It quantizes a continuous
 * signal (like viewport width) into discrete, named states (like "compact"
 * and "wide"). This is fundamentally different from media queries:
 *
 *   - Media queries are CSS-only and can't be shared with JS or the server.
 *   - Boundaries are data. They can be evaluated on the server (edge),
 *     the client (satellite directive), or in tests (pure function).
 *   - Boundaries are content-addressed: change the definition and the
 *     hash changes, automatically invalidating caches.
 *
 * In this tutorial you will:
 *   1. Import a boundary definition (viewport.boundaries.ts)
 *   2. Label the element with data-czap="viewport" for the Vite macro
 *   3. Spread satelliteAttrs() to wire boundary JSON + the satellite directive
 *   4. Write CSS that targets data-czap-state="compact|wide"
 */

import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { satelliteAttrs } from '@czap/astro';
import { viewport } from '../boundaries/viewport.boundaries.js';
---

<Base title="Your First Boundary">

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 1: What is a Boundary?
       ============================================================

       A boundary is a pure data structure that maps a continuous
       numeric signal to discrete named states. Think of it as a
       lookup table:

         viewport.width >= 0   --> "compact"
         viewport.width >= 768 --> "wide"

       The definition lives in src/boundaries/viewport.boundaries.ts.
       It's just a call to Boundary.make() from @czap/core.
  -->

  <h1>01 -- Your First Boundary</h1>

  <p>
    A <strong>boundary</strong> is czap's core primitive. It quantizes a
    continuous signal (viewport width, device memory, network speed) into
    discrete named states. Unlike media queries, boundaries are portable
    data -- they work on the server, the client, and in tests.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Key idea:</strong> Boundaries separate the <em>decision</em>
    (which state are we in?) from the <em>effect</em> (what does that state
    look like?). The decision is data. The effect is CSS.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 2: The Boundary Definition

       This code block shows what the boundary looks like in TypeScript.
       It's imported from src/boundaries/viewport.boundaries.ts.
  -->

  <h2>The Definition</h2>

  <pre><code>import {'{'} Boundary {'}'} from '@czap/core';

export const viewport = Boundary.make({'{'}&br;
  input: 'viewport.width',
  at: [
    [0, 'compact'],   // 0px and up = compact
    [768, 'wide'],    // 768px and up = wide
  ],
{'}'});</code></pre>

  <p>
    <code>Boundary.make()</code> returns an immutable, content-addressed
    object. Its <code>id</code> is an FNV-1a hash of the definition --
    change anything and the hash changes. This makes cache invalidation
    automatic.
  </p>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 3: Wiring It Up

       Spread {@link satelliteAttrs} from @czap/astro — it serializes the
       boundary, sets data-czap-directive="satellite", and optional
       data-czap-state for SSR. Pair it with data-czap="viewport" so the
       Vite plugin resolves the named export at build time.

       Under the hood, satelliteAttrs emits the same attributes you could
       hand-roll: data-czap-boundary='{...}', data-czap-directive, and
       data-czap-state. Manual wiring is fine for debugging; prefer the
       helper in app code.
  -->

  <h2>Wiring It Up</h2>

  <p>
    Import the boundary and spread <code>satelliteAttrs</code> onto your
    container (plus <code>data-czap="viewport"</code> for macro resolution):
  </p>

  <pre><code>import {'{'} satelliteAttrs {'}'} from '@czap/astro';
import {'{'} viewport {'}'} from '../boundaries/viewport.boundaries.js';

&lt;div
  data-czap="viewport"
  {'{'}...satelliteAttrs({'{'} boundary: viewport, initialState: 'compact' {'}'}){'}'}
&gt;
  ...content that adapts...
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 4: Live Demo

       This is the actual live boundary. Resize your browser window
       to see data-czap-state toggle between "compact" and "wide".

       The CSS below targets:
         [data-czap-state="compact"] .demo-card  --> stacked layout
         [data-czap-state="wide"] .demo-card     --> side-by-side layout

       No media queries. The satellite directive manages the state
       attribute; CSS just reacts to it.
  -->

  <h2>Live Demo</h2>

  <p>
    Resize your browser window across the 768px threshold. Watch the
    layout switch between stacked (compact) and side-by-side (wide).
  </p>

  <div
    data-czap="viewport"
    {...satelliteAttrs({ boundary: viewport, initialState: 'compact', class: 'boundary-demo' })}
  >
    <!-- --------------------------------------------------------
         These cards are the content that adapts. In compact state
         they stack vertically. In wide state they sit side by side.
         The transition is CSS-only -- the satellite directive just
         flips the data-czap-state attribute.
    -------------------------------------------------------- -->

    <div class="demo-card">
      <h3>Card A</h3>
      <p>This card adapts to the viewport boundary state.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="demo-card">
      <h3>Card B</h3>
      <p>No media queries -- just data-czap-state and CSS.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 5: Understanding the CSS

       The CSS uses attribute selectors to target boundary states.
       This is the "effect" side of the boundary/effect split.

       [data-czap-state="compact"] targets the compact state.
       [data-czap-state="wide"] targets the wide state.

       The transition property smooths the layout change -- czap
       encourages smooth state transitions rather than hard cuts.
  -->

  <h2>How the CSS Works</h2>

  <pre><code>/* Compact: single-column stack */
.boundary-demo[data-czap-state="compact"] {'{'}&br;
  flex-direction: column;
{'}'}

/* Wide: two-column row */
.boundary-demo[data-czap-state="wide"] {'{'}&br;
  flex-direction: row;
{'}'}</code></pre>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Why not media queries?</strong> Media queries work, but they're
    CSS-only. Boundaries can be evaluated anywhere: on the edge to pick the
    right HTML variant, in a test to assert behavior, or in a design tool to
    preview states. The same definition, everywhere.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 6: What's Next

       Now that you understand boundaries, the next tutorial
       introduces design tokens -- named values that vary across
       axes like theme and density.
  -->

  <h2>What You Learned</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><code>Boundary.make()</code> creates a content-addressed boundary definition.</li>
    <li><code>data-czap-boundary</code> serializes the boundary for the client.</li>
    <li><code>data-czap-state</code> holds the current evaluated state.</li>
    <li><code>client:satellite</code> hydrates the boundary with live signal evaluation.</li>
    <li>CSS attribute selectors target each state -- no JavaScript layout logic.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Next:</strong> <a href="/02-tokens">02 -- Design Tokens</a> --
    learn how czap tokens become CSS custom properties.
  </p>

</Base>

<!-- ================================================================
     Scoped styles for this tutorial page.

     The key pattern: use [data-czap-state="..."] attribute selectors
     to apply different visual treatments per boundary state. The
     satellite directive keeps data-czap-state in sync with the
     actual viewport width.
================================================================ -->

<style>
  .boundary-demo {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    transition: flex-direction 0.3s ease;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  /* Compact state: stack vertically */
  .boundary-demo[data-czap-state="compact"] {
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  /* Wide state: lay out horizontally */
  .boundary-demo[data-czap-state="wide"] {
    flex-direction: row;
  }

  .demo-card {
    flex: 1;
    background: #fff;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .demo-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .demo-card h3 {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    color: #4f46e5;
  }
</style>
